00:58:45.260 --> 00:58:47.243
- [Man] Dr. Jablonski,
that was really dynamic,

00:58:47.243 --> 00:58:49.468
thank you so much.

00:58:49.468 --> 00:58:52.355
As I mentioned yesterday,
my wife and I want to move

00:58:52.355 --> 00:58:55.833
to University Park and sneak
into some of your lectures

00:58:55.833 --> 00:58:58.146
so that we can hear more of you.

00:58:58.146 --> 00:59:00.146
But my question is this.

00:59:01.062 --> 00:59:04.897
As humanity continues to
move into urban areas,

00:59:04.897 --> 00:59:08.253
as we continue to cover
ourselves with clothing,

00:59:08.253 --> 00:59:11.003
not just our bodies but our head,

00:59:11.914 --> 00:59:14.414
is the evolution, well from a,

00:59:15.988 --> 00:59:20.155
natural selection perspective,
is our evolutionary

00:59:21.619 --> 00:59:24.286
result going to be lighter skin?

00:59:26.959 --> 00:59:28.802
- It's a very good question.

00:59:28.802 --> 00:59:33.491
And the answer is pretty
simple in that there is,

00:59:33.491 --> 00:59:37.567
we see no evidence of natural selection

00:59:37.567 --> 00:59:40.577
promoting depigmentation now,

00:59:40.577 --> 00:59:44.327
largely because there
is very little evidence

00:59:45.434 --> 00:59:47.101
of people losing out

00:59:48.575 --> 00:59:51.188
in the reproductive sweepstakes

00:59:51.188 --> 00:59:53.771
as a result of living in cities

00:59:54.889 --> 00:59:56.639
without sun exposure.

00:59:57.660 --> 01:00:00.271
So there might be some,

01:00:00.271 --> 01:00:03.913
if our epidemiological
studies were good enough,

01:00:03.913 --> 01:00:07.105
we may be able to detect some signal

01:00:07.105 --> 01:00:09.363
of sort of loss of fitness as a result

01:00:09.363 --> 01:00:14.036
of urban lifestyles, but not
enough to promote changes

01:00:14.036 --> 01:00:19.026
in gene frequency, leading
to changes in pigmentation.

01:00:19.026 --> 01:00:22.110
But what we do see in urban environments

01:00:22.110 --> 01:00:25.144
and this is one of the
beautiful parts of the Bay area,

01:00:25.144 --> 01:00:26.932
literally, physically beautiful,

01:00:26.932 --> 01:00:30.849
is that we see such lavish
admixture of people.

01:00:32.316 --> 01:00:35.209
People from all different
parts of the world

01:00:35.209 --> 01:00:39.292
come together, share
interesting cultural things,

01:00:40.391 --> 01:00:44.394
have children together, and
produce new genetic combinations

01:00:44.394 --> 01:00:45.977
and new phenotypes.

01:00:47.118 --> 01:00:50.737
And often these phenotypes are lighter

01:00:50.737 --> 01:00:52.821
than at least one of the parents.

01:00:52.821 --> 01:00:56.571
So we aren't seeing
natural selection produce

01:00:57.490 --> 01:00:59.112
loss of pigmentation.

01:00:59.112 --> 01:01:02.177
But we are seeing sort of a mingling

01:01:02.177 --> 01:01:06.333
and an increasing number of
pigmentation intermediates

01:01:06.333 --> 01:01:10.500
being produced in many
urban centers in the world.

01:01:13.590 --> 01:01:16.624
- [Man] I was fascinated
by your graph yesterday

01:01:16.624 --> 01:01:19.791
of decreasing hair in our hominid line

01:01:22.629 --> 01:01:26.379
in more recently thousand,
millions of years.

01:01:27.932 --> 01:01:31.583
And that raises two questions that I wish

01:01:31.583 --> 01:01:33.471
I had asked yesterday.

01:01:33.471 --> 01:01:36.804
One is that, as I follow your discussion

01:01:37.654 --> 01:01:40.916
of hairlessness and thermal regulation,

01:01:40.916 --> 01:01:44.141
I wonder if actually losing hair

01:01:44.141 --> 01:01:45.641
gave our ancestors

01:01:47.897 --> 01:01:51.922
a flexibility to exploit
a much wider range

01:01:51.922 --> 01:01:54.839
of environments than other primates

01:01:56.639 --> 01:01:58.045
who had more hair.

01:01:58.045 --> 01:02:00.562
In other words, a loss of
hair actually gave humans

01:02:00.562 --> 01:02:03.388
a lot of flexibility to go into a lot

01:02:03.388 --> 01:02:05.486
of very, very different environments.

01:02:05.486 --> 01:02:08.139
And my second question
about hair is one thing

01:02:08.139 --> 01:02:09.873
that we've noticed in nutrition

01:02:09.873 --> 01:02:12.846
that if you're feeding
an animal like a mouse

01:02:12.846 --> 01:02:14.859
or a rat that's full of hair,

01:02:14.859 --> 01:02:17.321
you have different requirements

01:02:17.321 --> 01:02:20.063
for sulfur-containing amino acids.

01:02:20.063 --> 01:02:22.065
And I was wondering if there was actually

01:02:22.065 --> 01:02:25.996
a nutritional component
in the loss of hair

01:02:25.996 --> 01:02:27.663
in our own ancestry.

01:02:29.511 --> 01:02:30.928
- Good questions.

01:02:32.322 --> 01:02:37.174
In answer to the first, I
think much of human versatility

01:02:37.174 --> 01:02:41.220
and our ability to disperse
and adapt to a wide range

01:02:41.220 --> 01:02:45.815
of environments is due to
our incredible technology

01:02:45.815 --> 01:02:50.137
and behavioral flexibility and
our incredible inventiveness,

01:02:50.137 --> 01:02:54.225
which we have had since the
beginning of Homo sapiens

01:02:54.225 --> 01:02:56.641
and probably even further.

01:02:56.641 --> 01:02:59.596
When we look at the
cultural sophistication

01:02:59.596 --> 01:03:02.704
of Neanderthals and
ancestors of Neanderthals

01:03:02.704 --> 01:03:04.863
that were living over 200,000 years ago,

01:03:04.863 --> 01:03:08.711
and modern humans in Africa
and outside of Africa

01:03:08.711 --> 01:03:10.560
tens of thousands of years ago,

01:03:10.560 --> 01:03:14.727
basically what you have
is a rich material culture

01:03:15.621 --> 01:03:19.704
and a rich culture of the
mind that allows people

01:03:20.635 --> 01:03:23.382
to live in places and under conditions

01:03:23.382 --> 01:03:27.950
and following lifestyles that
other mammals cannot achieve.

01:03:27.950 --> 01:03:31.867
So I think skin has played
a role in that it is

01:03:37.212 --> 01:03:41.330
given us a different
mode of communication,

01:03:41.330 --> 01:03:46.207
cutaneous communication,
communication through arraignment

01:03:46.207 --> 01:03:48.379
as well as our body decoration,

01:03:48.379 --> 01:03:50.686
has given us greater versatility.

01:03:50.686 --> 01:03:52.836
We don't just have one outfit,

01:03:52.836 --> 01:03:55.816
like you know, a dog or
a cat or a cow might have

01:03:55.816 --> 01:03:57.566
just sort of one fur,

01:04:00.025 --> 01:04:01.168
we have many.

01:04:01.168 --> 01:04:04.751
So we're able to express
our individuality,

01:04:05.931 --> 01:04:10.098
our group identity, through
how we adorn our naked bodies.

01:04:11.088 --> 01:04:12.961
And I think that has
been part of the cultural

01:04:12.961 --> 01:04:16.036
adaptation to different environments.

01:04:16.036 --> 01:04:18.786
In connection with diet and hair,

01:04:20.792 --> 01:04:24.883
the biggest things that
we notice in humans,

01:04:24.883 --> 01:04:28.472
of course our gross protein deprivation

01:04:28.472 --> 01:04:32.472
and the effects on hair
leading to hair breakage

01:04:33.645 --> 01:04:37.554
and the conspicuous sort of red pigment

01:04:37.554 --> 01:04:41.721
that you see in infants and
children with kwashiorkor.

01:04:43.658 --> 01:04:45.825
Other nutritional benefits

01:04:47.964 --> 01:04:50.297
are not that well understood

01:04:51.205 --> 01:04:54.806
and there are all manners of diets

01:04:54.806 --> 01:04:57.795
that people now subscribe
to for better hair,

01:04:57.795 --> 01:05:01.462
making your hair more
luxurious, less kinky,

01:05:03.457 --> 01:05:07.763
more wavy, what have you,
by eating certain foods.

01:05:07.763 --> 01:05:11.730
The extent to which diet,
beyond providing basic

01:05:11.730 --> 01:05:14.970
amino acids, the extent
to which modifying diet

01:05:14.970 --> 01:05:18.889
is going to affect hair texture and curl

01:05:18.889 --> 01:05:21.215
is really unclear.

01:05:21.215 --> 01:05:24.631
So there's a lot of sort of
bad science and pseudoscience

01:05:24.631 --> 01:05:27.214
about this, but I hope largely,

01:05:28.989 --> 01:05:33.173
or partly through the work of
graduate students in my lab,

01:05:33.173 --> 01:05:37.310
that we may be able to
understand some of these factors

01:05:37.310 --> 01:05:40.477
a bit more in two to four years' time.

01:05:42.163 --> 01:05:45.772
- [Woman] Hi, I actually
have a burning question.

01:05:45.772 --> 01:05:47.146
- Please.
- If you could talk a little

01:05:47.146 --> 01:05:49.930
bit more about the
difference between vitamin D3

01:05:49.930 --> 01:05:51.958
and vitamin D2.

01:05:51.958 --> 01:05:55.188
Because I'm really
curious about two things.

01:05:55.188 --> 01:05:58.188
One is as we move to fortified milk,

01:05:59.921 --> 01:06:01.632
and I actually don't now
much about the history

01:06:01.632 --> 01:06:03.153
of when we did that and
what was the impetus

01:06:03.153 --> 01:06:05.580
for doing it, how much of a health benefit

01:06:05.580 --> 01:06:07.277
has that conferred?

01:06:07.277 --> 01:06:11.244
And then also, is that
actually adequate to help

01:06:11.244 --> 01:06:15.747
circumvent some of the
deleterious health effects.

01:06:15.747 --> 01:06:17.548
- Really good questions.

01:06:17.548 --> 01:06:20.865
Vitamin D2 is a form of vitamin D

01:06:20.865 --> 01:06:24.608
that is produced primarily in plants.

01:06:24.608 --> 01:06:28.164
When we ingest it, we can use it,

01:06:28.164 --> 01:06:31.995
but it has to undergo and
additional hydroxylation step

01:06:31.995 --> 01:06:32.917
in the liver.

01:06:32.917 --> 01:06:37.084
So vitamin D3 is the more
common animal origin vitamin D,

01:06:38.679 --> 01:06:42.766
although there is some
vitamin D3 in some plants,

01:06:42.766 --> 01:06:44.721
but vitamin D2 is the more common.

01:06:44.721 --> 01:06:47.721
Both of them are potentially usable,

01:06:48.723 --> 01:06:51.284
but both of them when we ingest them

01:06:51.284 --> 01:06:55.225
as food or as supplements, have to undergo

01:06:55.225 --> 01:06:59.518
the rigorous conversion in
the liver, in the kidney,

01:06:59.518 --> 01:07:04.179
and that final step of chemical
conversion in the kidney

01:07:04.179 --> 01:07:06.757
to the active form of vitamin D,

01:07:06.757 --> 01:07:11.547
that can occur from a
vitamin D2 or D3 precursor,

01:07:11.547 --> 01:07:15.714
and that is the most
rate-controlled step in the body,

01:07:16.709 --> 01:07:21.315
so that you can produce
a lot of vitamin serum D3

01:07:21.315 --> 01:07:23.185
in its storage form,

01:07:23.185 --> 01:07:27.061
but then the activation
to active D3 that occurs

01:07:27.061 --> 01:07:29.952
in the kidney is extremely
highly controlled.

01:07:29.952 --> 01:07:33.952
But these days, most
supplements are vitamin D3.

01:07:35.534 --> 01:07:37.156
There are fewer of D2.

01:07:37.156 --> 01:07:41.930
In answer to your question
about fortification in milk,

01:07:41.930 --> 01:07:45.800
milk fortification was
introduced in this country,

01:07:45.800 --> 01:07:48.300
widespread, after World War II

01:07:49.751 --> 01:07:53.918
when the importance of vitamin
D in preventing rickets

01:07:55.762 --> 01:07:58.908
in infants and children
was widely recognized.

01:07:58.908 --> 01:08:02.203
And it was a public health remediation

01:08:02.203 --> 01:08:05.036
that was initiated similar to that

01:08:06.741 --> 01:08:10.158
of fluoridated water for the public good.

01:08:12.823 --> 01:08:16.051
In this country, most milk that you buy

01:08:16.051 --> 01:08:17.914
is vitamin D fortified.

01:08:17.914 --> 01:08:21.927
But the amount of vitamin D
varies from one brand of milk

01:08:21.927 --> 01:08:24.909
and even from one batch
of milk to the other.

01:08:24.909 --> 01:08:27.548
The level of vitamin D fortification

01:08:27.548 --> 01:08:29.215
is enough to prevent

01:08:31.362 --> 01:08:34.362
the most severe level of deficiency,

01:08:35.482 --> 01:08:36.982
but not to provide

01:08:39.353 --> 01:08:43.270
physiological adequacy
for a child or an adult,

01:08:46.122 --> 01:08:48.685
unless you drank
prodigious amounts of milk

01:08:48.685 --> 01:08:51.043
that would be dangerous
from the point of view

01:08:51.043 --> 01:08:52.538
of drinking too much calcium

01:08:52.538 --> 01:08:55.344
and putting you at a
risk for kidney stones.

01:08:55.344 --> 01:08:59.511
So the vitamin D3 fortification
in milk is very helpful

01:09:01.483 --> 01:09:04.652
and could be used as a
model for other countries.

01:09:04.652 --> 01:09:07.384
There are lots of places where milk is not

01:09:07.384 --> 01:09:09.903
vitamin D fortified and
where this would help

01:09:09.903 --> 01:09:14.787
to sort of lower the prevalence
of vitamin D deficiency

01:09:14.787 --> 01:09:18.004
in some very vulnerable populations.

01:09:18.004 --> 01:09:21.979
But that level of
fortification is not adequate

01:09:21.979 --> 01:09:24.438
to meet physiological needs.

01:09:24.438 --> 01:09:28.231
So one has to have other
vitamin D-rich foods,

01:09:28.231 --> 01:09:30.600
of which there aren't very many.

01:09:30.600 --> 01:09:32.913
Oily fish is the best source,

01:09:32.913 --> 01:09:36.011
but there are few
genuinely oily fish around,

01:09:36.011 --> 01:09:39.761
and so today, most people
really have to rely

01:09:41.145 --> 01:09:42.885
on vitamin D supplements

01:09:42.885 --> 01:09:45.885
and occasional prudent sun exposure.

01:09:50.727 --> 01:09:52.350
- [Man] You timed your visit well.

01:09:52.350 --> 01:09:55.186
You joined us in a sunny
interlude in an otherwise

01:09:55.186 --> 01:09:56.603
very dark winter.

01:09:57.652 --> 01:10:00.119
And that prompts my question.

01:10:00.119 --> 01:10:03.060
I notice a lightening of the
mood when the sun is out.

01:10:03.060 --> 01:10:07.227
And I wonder whether that
mood sensitivity to sunlight

01:10:08.490 --> 01:10:11.073
could be related to a person's,

01:10:13.331 --> 01:10:17.748
the location of the
evolution of their genotype.

01:10:17.748 --> 01:10:21.859
- This is a great question,
and many people have been

01:10:21.859 --> 01:10:24.101
interested in this in trying to understand

01:10:24.101 --> 01:10:27.118
the biological basis and the genetic basis

01:10:27.118 --> 01:10:29.478
for seasonal affective disorder,

01:10:29.478 --> 01:10:33.118
and the role that vitamin D might play.

01:10:33.118 --> 01:10:37.219
This is a fascinating
and complicated answer.

01:10:37.219 --> 01:10:40.453
I'm gonna give you the short version.

01:10:40.453 --> 01:10:43.703
What we have in our retinas of our eyes

01:10:45.813 --> 01:10:49.092
are not only the three kinds of cones

01:10:49.092 --> 01:10:52.811
that allow us to see beautiful
trichromatic color vision,

01:10:52.811 --> 01:10:56.096
but we also have a
specialized subset of cones

01:10:56.096 --> 01:10:58.774
that are blue light receptors.

01:10:58.774 --> 01:11:01.922
So on a bright day like this,

01:11:01.922 --> 01:11:06.089
there is a lot of very short
wavelength visible light

01:11:07.894 --> 01:11:10.353
that stimulates the blue light receptors

01:11:10.353 --> 01:11:12.973
that makes us more
alert, that communicates

01:11:12.973 --> 01:11:15.049
with our pineal gland that communicates

01:11:15.049 --> 01:11:17.049
with our pituitary gland

01:11:18.555 --> 01:11:22.722
that communicates, sort of
the global endocrine switches

01:11:24.209 --> 01:11:25.376
are turned on.

01:11:26.885 --> 01:11:30.552
And many of these lead
to elevation of mood.

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:36.167
Beautiful work has been done comparing

01:11:38.499 --> 01:11:42.085
the prevalence of seasonal
affective disorder

01:11:42.085 --> 01:11:46.069
in places like Iceland versus Ecuador.

01:11:46.069 --> 01:11:50.810
And what is found is that
there are real differences

01:11:50.810 --> 01:11:53.060
in the amount of blue light

01:11:55.004 --> 01:11:57.087
that stimulates the body,

01:11:58.258 --> 01:12:01.400
and that this seems to be
one of the most important

01:12:01.400 --> 01:12:03.455
arbiters of mood.

01:12:03.455 --> 01:12:05.705
Vitamin D also contributes,

01:12:07.054 --> 01:12:09.833
but interestingly it is not probably

01:12:09.833 --> 01:12:13.593
the primary contributor to
seasonal affective disorder,

01:12:13.593 --> 01:12:16.050
or the sort of the high that you feel.

01:12:16.050 --> 01:12:20.217
Rather it's the stimulation
of your blue light receptors.

01:12:24.096 --> 01:12:27.128
- [Man] I think milk was
the wrong thing to fortify,

01:12:27.128 --> 01:12:30.906
because 50 million people in
the US are lactose intolerant,

01:12:30.906 --> 01:12:34.190
and most African-Americans
are lactose intolerant.

01:12:34.190 --> 01:12:38.992
So, we should figure out
what to put vitamin D in.

01:12:38.992 --> 01:12:41.275
Now, I've been converting lots of people

01:12:41.275 --> 01:12:43.432
to take vitamin D.

01:12:43.432 --> 01:12:44.677
And if they're deficient,

01:12:44.677 --> 01:12:47.728
they really feel terrific afterwards.

01:12:47.728 --> 01:12:50.395
So there is, whether it's Danes,

01:12:51.483 --> 01:12:55.126
I was in Denmark for a scientific meeting

01:12:55.126 --> 01:12:58.046
and Denmark has, Copenhagen
has about the worst climate

01:12:58.046 --> 01:13:02.246
in the world, at least
compared to Californians.

01:13:02.246 --> 01:13:05.770
And it was a sunny day and
the whole city stopped.

01:13:05.770 --> 01:13:09.364
Everybody had taken off
most of their clothes.

01:13:09.364 --> 01:13:10.959
I must say more clothes were taken off

01:13:10.959 --> 01:13:12.553
than an American would.

01:13:12.553 --> 01:13:14.381
And there were all of
these half-naked bodies

01:13:14.381 --> 01:13:16.749
all over the city all day.

01:13:16.749 --> 01:13:19.047
Everybody was just,
nobody was in the shops,

01:13:19.047 --> 01:13:21.649
nobody was doing anything but sunbathing.

01:13:21.649 --> 01:13:23.431
I asked a Danish scientist friend,

01:13:23.431 --> 01:13:25.092
"How come you do this?"

01:13:25.092 --> 01:13:28.404
He said, "Well, we
Scandinavians get so little sun,

01:13:28.404 --> 01:13:31.950
"that whenever there's sun, we sunbathe,

01:13:31.950 --> 01:13:34.403
"because we feel terrific afterwards."

01:13:34.403 --> 01:13:37.956
And I've had personal experience
with African-Americans

01:13:37.956 --> 01:13:40.499
who I've gotten to take vitamin D,

01:13:40.499 --> 01:13:42.138
and they feel terrific.

01:13:42.138 --> 01:13:45.771
So I think that's something that'll help--

01:13:45.771 --> 01:13:49.938
- Yes, and you know, in connection
with both of your points,

01:13:51.017 --> 01:13:53.814
first of all, getting a vehicle

01:13:53.814 --> 01:13:56.109
other than milk is important.

01:13:56.109 --> 01:13:59.217
In South Africa there is fortification

01:13:59.217 --> 01:14:00.717
of some margarine.

01:14:01.641 --> 01:14:04.072
Unfortunately, you would
have to eat a huge amount

01:14:04.072 --> 01:14:06.275
of margarine in order to benefit

01:14:06.275 --> 01:14:08.653
from the vitamin D fortification.

01:14:08.653 --> 01:14:11.720
One of the problems is that
vitamin D is oil-soluble,

01:14:11.720 --> 01:14:15.887
so you can't easily sort of
put it into fortified cereals

01:14:17.624 --> 01:14:20.967
or orange juice, although
people do put it into

01:14:20.967 --> 01:14:23.384
the orange juice suspensions.

01:14:24.320 --> 01:14:27.733
But it's a difficult molecule to deliver

01:14:27.733 --> 01:14:30.733
in a fortification of a normal food.

01:14:32.061 --> 01:14:35.312
But your point about Denmark
is a very interesting one,

01:14:35.312 --> 01:14:40.027
because there they have
refused to fortify their milk.

01:14:40.027 --> 01:14:43.475
So there is no baseline
fortification of milk

01:14:43.475 --> 01:14:46.485
or any dairy products,
and people can only get

01:14:46.485 --> 01:14:49.005
their vitamin D either from fish

01:14:49.005 --> 01:14:51.758
or by taking off their clothes.

01:14:51.758 --> 01:14:55.203
And they really, you
know you have sort of,

01:14:55.203 --> 01:14:57.897
I don't want to impune the Danes at all,

01:14:57.897 --> 01:15:02.064
but people sort of going to
their paleolithic sort of

01:15:03.403 --> 01:15:06.153
past to expose themselves to sun.

01:15:07.225 --> 01:15:10.225
And I think what's interesting there

01:15:11.274 --> 01:15:15.568
is that when people are exposed to the sun

01:15:15.568 --> 01:15:18.739
that their ancestors were used to,

01:15:18.739 --> 01:15:22.885
you know if they gradually
sort of gain and lose

01:15:22.885 --> 01:15:26.335
sun exposure or UV
exposure, their skin changes

01:15:26.335 --> 01:15:30.502
and they're able to maintain
UV or vitamin D adequacy.

01:15:31.451 --> 01:15:33.729
And in a country like Denmark,

01:15:33.729 --> 01:15:37.612
when people were outside most of the time,

01:15:37.612 --> 01:15:40.788
even though they had
vitamin D in their diet,

01:15:40.788 --> 01:15:44.272
they got a lot of their
physiologically important

01:15:44.272 --> 01:15:47.961
vitamin D throughout
the year from episodic,

01:15:47.961 --> 01:15:50.794
but regular episodic sun exposure.

01:15:52.119 --> 01:15:53.678
- [Man] They were also
eating a lot of fish.

01:15:53.678 --> 01:15:56.796
- Yes, yes, much of which
doesn't exist anymore,

01:15:56.796 --> 01:15:59.612
or is too expensive
for most people to buy.

01:15:59.612 --> 01:16:02.761
- [Man] Now, vitamin D
isn't that expensive.

01:16:02.761 --> 01:16:05.011
- Ah, it's here now, today,

01:16:07.132 --> 01:16:09.202
in the United States, vitamin D is cheap.

01:16:09.202 --> 01:16:11.537
You can go into any
supermarket, any health store,

01:16:11.537 --> 01:16:15.204
get these huge bottles
for 10 bucks or less.

01:16:16.883 --> 01:16:19.966
But go to Europe, go to South Africa,

01:16:20.870 --> 01:16:22.414
and try to buy vitamin D.

01:16:22.414 --> 01:16:24.777
It's not bulk processed there,

01:16:24.777 --> 01:16:27.432
and a little bottle of 60 capsules

01:16:27.432 --> 01:16:29.589
will cost you $20.

01:16:29.589 --> 01:16:32.589
Or it'll cost you more
than that in South Africa

01:16:32.589 --> 01:16:35.218
because it's imported from
the United States or Europe

01:16:35.218 --> 01:16:38.367
and it's more than a week's wages.

01:16:38.367 --> 01:16:41.096
- [Man] But at least in fortification

01:16:41.096 --> 01:16:44.460
and telling people here,
you can buy vitamin D,

01:16:44.460 --> 01:16:46.024
it's not that expensive.

01:16:46.024 --> 01:16:49.191
- And I think, this is something where

01:16:50.268 --> 01:16:54.876
the medical establishment
is moving significantly

01:16:54.876 --> 01:16:57.434
and importantly to
recognize the importance

01:16:57.434 --> 01:17:00.212
of vitamin D supplementation.

01:17:00.212 --> 01:17:02.109
It's not the be all and the end all.

01:17:02.109 --> 01:17:05.047
It's not a panacea by any means.

01:17:05.047 --> 01:17:09.051
But raising people off
of baseline deficiency

01:17:09.051 --> 01:17:11.434
will greatly improve health outcomes,

01:17:11.434 --> 01:17:13.596
not only in the ways that I've described,

01:17:13.596 --> 01:17:14.789
but in many others.

01:17:14.789 --> 01:17:17.046
- [Man] You know, I've been
digging into that for years now

01:17:17.046 --> 01:17:21.027
and there's a huge, I
think dark-skinned people

01:17:21.027 --> 01:17:23.840
are carrying a big weight on their back.

01:17:23.840 --> 01:17:26.199
And vitamin D is going to help.

01:17:26.199 --> 01:17:27.032
- Yes.

01:17:28.547 --> 01:17:30.041
- Well thank you, if you
have no more questions,

01:17:30.041 --> 01:17:32.039
if we could do a big round of applause

01:17:32.039 --> 01:17:33.275
and a thank you for Nina.

01:17:33.275 --> 01:17:36.442
(audience applauding)

